Refreshing a 2-node Oracle RAC production database to a 2-node Oracle RAC development database using RMAN can be done in two ways:

1Ô∏è‚É£ With Some Downtime ‚Üí The production database is taken offline for a short period during the refresh.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Without Downtime (Using Data Guard or Active Duplication) ‚Üí The production database remains operational.

I'll provide both methods in a Windows environment.

üü¢ Method 1: Refreshing with Downtime (Cold Backup & Restore)
üîπ Pros: Simple, reliable.
üîπ Cons: Requires downtime.

üî∑ Step 1: Prepare the DEV Database for Refresh
Stop the DEV RAC database

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl stop database -d DEVDB
Remove the existing DEV database (Optional)

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl remove database -d DEVDB
üî∑ Step 2: Take RMAN Cold Backup of PROD RAC
Log in to RMAN from PROD node 1:

powershell
Copy
Edit
rman target / nocatalog
Shutdown the PROD database for consistent backup:

sql
Copy
Edit
SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE;
STARTUP MOUNT;
BACKUP DATABASE FORMAT 'E:\Backup\PROD_%U.bak';
BACKUP CURRENT CONTROLFILE FORMAT 'E:\Backup\PROD_ctl.bak';
Copy the Backup to the DEV Server
Use scp or robocopy to transfer E:\Backup\PROD_* to the DEV server.

üî∑ Step 3: Restore the Database on DEV
Mount the DEV instance:

powershell
Copy
Edit
rman target / nocatalog
sql
Copy
Edit
STARTUP NOMOUNT;
Restore Control File:

sql
Copy
Edit
RESTORE CONTROLFILE FROM 'E:\Backup\PROD_ctl.bak';
Mount the Database:

sql
Copy
Edit
ALTER DATABASE MOUNT;
Restore Database Files:

sql
Copy
Edit
RESTORE DATABASE FROM 'E:\Backup\PROD_%U.bak';
Recover the Database:

sql
Copy
Edit
RECOVER DATABASE;
Open the Database with RESETLOGS:

sql
Copy
Edit
ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS;
Recreate DEV RAC Configuration:

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl add database -d DEVDB -o C:\oracle\product\19.0.0\dbhome_1
Start RAC Services:

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl start database -d DEVDB
üîπ DEV RAC is now refreshed with the latest PROD data!

üü¢ Method 2: Refreshing with Zero Downtime (Using RMAN Active Duplicate)
üîπ Pros: No downtime for PROD.
üîπ Cons: Requires additional storage & network bandwidth.

üî∑ Step 1: Prepare the DEV Database for Active Duplication
Stop the DEV database:

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl stop database -d DEVDB
Delete old DEV datafiles:

powershell
Copy
Edit
del /s /q E:\oracle\oradata\DEVDB\
Ensure the TNS setup allows PROD ‚Üí DEV connection.
Update tnsnames.ora on PROD:

plaintext
Copy
Edit
DEVDB =
  (DESCRIPTION =
    (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCP)(HOST = dev-rac-node1)(PORT = 1521))
    (CONNECT_DATA =
      (SERVER = DEDICATED)
      (SERVICE_NAME = DEVDB)
    )
  )
üî∑ Step 2: Start DEV Database in NOMOUNT
powershell
Copy
Edit
sqlplus / as sysdba
sql
Copy
Edit
STARTUP NOMOUNT;
üî∑ Step 3: Run RMAN Active Duplicate from PROD
On PROD Node 1:

powershell
Copy
Edit
rman target sys/ProdPwd@PRODDB auxiliary sys/DevPwd@DEVDB
sql
Copy
Edit
DUPLICATE TARGET DATABASE FOR STANDBY FROM ACTIVE DATABASE 
TO NEW_LOCATION 'E:\oracle\oradata\DEVDB'
SPFILE 
SET DB_UNIQUE_NAME='DEVDB'
SET CONTROL_FILES='E:\oracle\oradata\DEVDB\control01.ctl'
SET LOG_FILE_NAME_CONVERT='/oracle/oradata/PRODDB','/oracle/oradata/DEVDB'
SET DB_FILE_NAME_CONVERT='/oracle/oradata/PRODDB','/oracle/oradata/DEVDB'
SET AUDIT_FILE_DEST='E:\oracle\admin\DEVDB\adump'
NOFILENAMECHECK;
üî∑ Step 4: Convert the Standby to a Primary DEV Database
Cancel Redo Apply:

sql
Copy
Edit
ALTER DATABASE RECOVER MANAGED STANDBY DATABASE CANCEL;
Activate the DEV Database:

sql
Copy
Edit
ALTER DATABASE ACTIVATE STANDBY DATABASE;
Open the Database with RESETLOGS:

sql
Copy
Edit
ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS;
Reconfigure DEV RAC:

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl add database -d DEVDB -o C:\oracle\product\19.0.0\dbhome_1
Start RAC Services:

powershell
Copy
Edit
srvctl start database -d DEVDB
üîπ DEV RAC is now refreshed with the latest PROD data with ZERO downtime!

üîµ Summary Table of Both Methods
Method	Downtime	Pros	Cons
Cold Backup & Restore	‚ùå Yes (Short Downtime)	Simple, Reliable	Requires DB Shutdown
Active Duplicate	‚úÖ No	Zero Downtime, Faster	Needs Extra Storage, High Bandwidth
